grantReference>RES-073-27-0022</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This project examines a specialist field of taxation, the form of tax evasion termed 'undeclared work' involving 'productive activities that are unregistered by or hidden from the public authorities for tax, benefit and/or labour law purposes' (OECD 2002). &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The project examines hidden work practices in UK, viewing 'hidden' work as a method of 'direct tax fraud' (National Audit Office 2003). The objectives are to evaluate the scale and nature of undeclared work and to also determine the policy implications of the findings, analysing what are the barriers to the formalisation of hidden work practices. Methodologically, it recognises the opportunities tax accounting research presents to engage in qualitative research. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The project involves direct survey methods, using a structured questionnaire, taking the household as the unit of analysis, followed by in-depth qualitative interviews. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The research will make a positive impact within the taxation field of Accounting&amp;nbsp;and Finance, responding to calls for taxation to be viewed as a social practice. The results will feed into debates within the UK policy-making community (National Audit Office, HMRC) regarding methods of enabling tax compliance and punishing non-compliance. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-06-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>50563</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>School visits</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Local</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>289497E7-3ECF-4BFC-B7BB-DA59B422E917</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Each year in 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015 - I have held research-led half day events at the Sheffield College and Longley Park College, Sheffield. Each event normally involves over 40 school-children/sixth formers getting involved in an interactive event, which has aimed to improve understanding of the role of taxation within UK society. Within these events, Dr. Rodgers has also highlighted his work within the Centre for Regional Economic and Enterprise Development (CREED) at Sheffield University and crucially engages the students with the research. The events typically involve:

1) An overview about the Sheffield University Management School and what life is like at the University
2) A presentation regarding the role of taxation in society
3) A presentation of research being undertaken on the nature of undeclared work and tax evasion in the UK economy
4) An interactive session in which students are encouraged to devise ways to engage with taxation from government, business and societal perspectives. 

I believe these events have provided an opportunity to engage students with issues relating to taxation based on my research in the area. Importantly the events will allow the young people to engage with and participate in discussions relating to the positive benefits of taxation before they enter the world of work. Also these events provide an excellent outreach opportunity. These events promote the ongoing 'Widening Participation' activities being undertaken by the Sheffield University Management School and the Faculty of Social Sciences.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>56ddbf98136ed8.32833469</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Schools</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2012,2013,2014,2015</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Radio Interview</gtr:description><gtr:form>A press release, press conference or response to a media enquiry/interview</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>DC50BC5A-88C5-4EED-8636-5E72E2D4EA11</gtr:id><gtr:impact>On two occasions, I have been contacted by Radio 4 and provided expert commentary and opinion regarding the nature of informal economic activity, being undertaken by migrants within UK today. This information was aired on the Radio 4 'Today' programme and also formed a relevant part of the 'Out of the Shadows' series, run by Radio 4, focusing on the nature of the informal economy in the UK.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>56ddc0d9212639.35330507</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2015</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>900</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>Uni